{"_id":"14176732-07c5-36dc-83e6-d2437f55cb3f","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"28dde5772b48c92e08b8050411aa5ba8","message":"The best approach is to only expose a synchronous OR asynchronous method.\r\n\r\nIf the underlying operation is naturally asynchronous (e.g., I/O-bound), then only expose an asynchronous API. If the underlying operation is naturally synchronous (e.g., CPU-bound), then only expose a synchronous API (leaving it up to the caller to decide whether they need to use Task.Run).","postId":"2013_11_taskrun-etiquette-examples-dont-use-a63e8aa8-3250-37a4-990d-af802d3197e6","replyTo":"72c8cec7-5854-362d-88f7-772c8f069df0","date":"2015-04-22T22:49:30Z","timestamp":1429742970,"authorUserId":"disqus:stephen_cleary"}